    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1343088512" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1343088512" />
    <a title="Gabrielle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6753400-gabrielle"><img alt="Gabrielle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1640971922p2/6753400.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1343088512?book_show_action=true">Jul 23, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gabrielle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gabrielle" href="/user/show/6753400-gabrielle">Gabrielle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780767931113" href="/book/show/7380399-the-angel-s-game">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6753400-gabrielle?shelf=gothic">gothic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6753400-gabrielle?shelf=ouch-my-feels">ouch-my-feels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6753400-gabrielle?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6753400-gabrielle?shelf=read-in-2020">read-in-2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6753400-gabrielle?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6753400-gabrielle?shelf=mystery">mystery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6753400-gabrielle?shelf=own-a-copy">own-a-copy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1343088512" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14267051624810762395">Updated review after a re-read in November 2020. Rest in piece, Mr. Ruiz Zafon: you have given me books that are real treasures and that I will revisit many times.<br/><br/>**<br/><br/>The Barcelona of “The Angel’s Game” is dark, dirty, dangerous. Zafon brings a city to life the same way my beloved China Mieville does; it’s a presence, a character. These books have made me want to travel to Barcelona, walk the tiny streets, look at the gorgeous Art Deco buildings, visit the cemetery overlooking the sea. I’m a city-</span>
  <span id="freeText14267051624810762395" style="display:none">Updated review after a re-read in November 2020. Rest in piece, Mr. Ruiz Zafon: you have given me books that are real treasures and that I will revisit many times.<br /><br />**<br /><br />The Barcelona of “The Angel’s Game” is dark, dirty, dangerous. Zafon brings a city to life the same way my beloved China Mieville does; it’s a presence, a character. These books have made me want to travel to Barcelona, walk the tiny streets, look at the gorgeous Art Deco buildings, visit the cemetery overlooking the sea. I’m a city-slicker, and when a writer manages to bring an urban setting to life this vividly, I am automatically enchanted. A story like this one could not have taken place anywhere else…<br /><br />It’s where David Martin lives. A young destitute orphan who is finally given a chance to write when his hero Pedro Vidal, star journalist of the “Voice of the Industry”, decides to let him try his hand at the old typewriter. A complicated mix of jealousy and guilt eventually pushes Vidal to get David fired. The poor young man is reduced to scraping a living writing penny dreadfuls… until a mysterious man offers him a very lucrative deal if he would write a very special book for him… But there might be more to this deal than David could have ever foreseen.<br /><br />This story takes place before “The Shadow of the Wind” (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/226430093">https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a>), but while I’m not sure the word “prequel” is the correct term, these stories are inextricably linked, and share many similar elements. Now about that: Zafon clearly loves his classics and his Gothic novels: no one can fault him for that, and that may be why he manages to write his stories as beautifully as he does. But as with any genres, there are tropes, and if you are going to accuse him of being unoriginal because he likes forbidden love stories, revenge-obsessed psychopaths, demonic and angelic imagery, burnt down buildings and drownings, you may just not be a fan of the Gothic genre in general… Stay away from these novels and be quiet. However, if you find all these things awesome, run to a bookstore and get everything my dear Carlos has ever written. No one does Neo-Gothic like this man. “The Angel’s Game” flirts a bit with the supernatural, but never overtly: it’s more magical realism than fantasy, and it’s just enough to be weird, just enough to spook.<br /><br />The prose is just as brutally beautiful as it was in “Shadow of the Wind”, rich and sensual. David is a wonderful blend of Pip and Mr. Rochester (both “Great Expectations” and “Jane Eyre” are referred to many times): hopeful, ambitious, sarcastic, passionate, grouchy. His old, crumbly house is full of dark secrets and strange noises. And Isabella… Lovely, stubborn, mouthy Isabella! At last, the strong female character I had been hoping for from Zafon! He still threw an ethereally beautiful useless one in there, but Isabella’s badassery makes up for it. The end breaks my heart, just as much as “Shadow of the Wind” did; if you liked the first one, I assure you the second book of this series is just as good and riveting.<br /><br />If you should happen to fall in love with David, the rest of the Cemetery of Forgotten Books series is not about him per se, but he does show up from time to time… I suggest reading them in order of publication.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14267051624810762395" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


